Simple Linear Regression - Week 9, Lecture 1

Author

Hector Gavilanes

An online retailer needs to manage the amount of time needed to select the ordered items and assemble them for shipping. In order to assess the amount of time (Time) his assemblers devote to this task, the retailer takes a random sample of 100 orders and records the number of items in each order (Noltems) and the time needed to assemble the shipment. The data are given here: Google Sheet.

Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(gsheet)
library(car)
library(gridExtra)

Data

# clear environment
rm(list = ls())

# extract data
data <- as_tibble(gsheet2tbl("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1xAsE0KmspC0dP4Uuyym33uU1G8ahI6z7wPVwts7BTRM/edit?usp=sharing"))
  1. Summarize the data using appropriate summary statistics.
summary(data$Time)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
   2.40   18.05   24.85   27.14   34.83   57.10
  1. Model the amount of time as a function of the number of items in the order.
m1 = data$Time ~ data$NoItems
time_model <- lm(m1)
summary(time_model)

Call:
lm(formula = m1)

Residuals:

Multiple R-squared:  0.8709,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.8696 
F-statistic:   661 on 1 and 98 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Model formula:

\[\hat{y} = 14.59 + 1.07{\text{ items}}\]

Interpretation

  • Before considering number of items, we expect the shipment time to be at 14.59 minutes.
  • For every item, we expect shipment time to increase by 1.07 minutes.
  • For every 10 items, we expect shipment time to increase by 11.17 minutes.
  1. Find the 95% confidence interval for \(\beta_1\).
confint(time_model)
                  2.5 %    97.5 %
(Intercept)  13.2767827 15.893416
data$NoItems  0.9828406  1.147253

The 95% CI for \(\beta_{items}\) is (0.98, 1.15)

  1. Use the appropriate hypothesis test to determine if the number of items in the order is a significant predictor of the amount of time to pick and ship the order. Test at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.

Hypotheses

  • \(H_0: \beta_{items} = 0\)
  • \(H_1: \beta_{items} \ne 0\)

Test Statistic

  • \(t_{0} = 25.71\)

p-Value

  • \(p < 0.001\)

Conclusion

Reject \(H_0\) at \(\alpha = 0.05\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that the number of items is a significant predictor for shipment time.

  1. State and assess the assumptions of linear regression. Is our model valid?

Assumptions

\(\varepsilon \overset{\text{iid}}{\sim} N(0, \sigma^2)\)

The residuals follow a normal distribution.

  • Normality is checked with the histogram and/or qq plot.

    • Mean \(\mu=0\)

  • Variance is checked with the scatter plot and/or the Brown-Forsythe-Levene.

    • Common variance \(\sigma^2\)

Assessment

# Assessment of Residuals
plot(time_model)

# histogram residuals
hist(time_model$residuals)

The model is valid. The Q-Q plot displays normality of residuals. Even though, the histogram is negatively shifted, it does not represent a concern. The residuals are relatively normal distributed.

However, the variance test is not suitable for this case because both are continuous variables.

  1. Find Spearmanâs correlation between the amount of time and the number of items and the corresponding 95% confidence interval.
# nonparametric correlation method to find coefficient
cor(data$Time, data$NoItems,
    use = "complete.obs",
    method = "spearman")
[1] 0.9311364
  1. State and assess the assumptions for Pearsonâs correlation. Is Pearsonâs correlation valid for this data?

Correlation

  • \(\rho\) = 0.931 indicates a very strong correlation.
  • It is a positive correlation; as Number of Items increases, Shipping Time increases

Pearsonâs Correlation Assumptions

  • The Pearsonâs correlation assumptions have not been met. Thus, the nonparametric Spearmanâs correlation test should be reported.
# QQ plot: Time
qq_time <- data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sample = Time)) +
    stat_qq(size=3) +
    stat_qq_line() +
    theme_minimal() +
    xlab("Theoretical") +
    ylab("Sample")+
  labs(title = "Time")

# QQ plot: Items
qq_items <- data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sample = NoItems)) +
    stat_qq(size=3) +
    stat_qq_line() +
    theme_minimal() +
    xlab("Theoretical") +
    ylab("Sample")+
  labs(title = "Number of Items")

# Combine both graphs
grid.arrange(qq_time, qq_items, nrow=1, top = "QQ Plot of Time by Items")

  1. Construct a visualization for the model. At the very least, you should have a scatterplot with a regression line overlaid.
data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = NoItems, y = Time))+
  geom_point(size=2, alpha=0.55, colour="orange")+
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x, method=lm, se=FALSE)+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title = "Linear Regression",
       x = "Number of Items per Order")

time_coef <- time_model$coefficients
time_coef
 (Intercept) data$NoItems 
   14.585099     1.065047 
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(y_hat = time_coef[1] + time_coef[2] * data$NoItems)

data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = NoItems, y = Time))+
  geom_point(size=2, alpha=0.55, colour="darkgray")+
  geom_line(aes(y = y_hat))+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title = "Linear Regression",
       x = "Number of Items per Order")
